  <!-- FAQ Section (9 Questions with 100+ words of real science each) -->
  <section class="py-16 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 max-w-4xl mx-auto border-t border-slate-800">
    <h2 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-white text-center mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      
      <!-- FAQ 1 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do optical illusions work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Optical illusions work by exploiting the lag and predictive nature of the human visual system. The eyes capture raw visual stimuli, but the brain must synthesize this data to form a coherent mental model of reality. Because processing the full field of vision in real-time is metabolically expensive and slow, the brain relies on top-down processing shortcuts based on past experiences, context, lighting priors, and geometry. When a visual stimulus contains conflicting features—such as contrasting gradients or ambiguous perspective lines—these predictive shortcuts fail. This creates a mismatch between reality and perception, resulting in an illusion.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 2 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Why do optical illusions work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Visual illusions exist because the human brain evolved to prioritize processing speed and decision efficiency over absolute scientific accuracy. In nature, a rapid, approximate guess about a hidden predator is far more survival-friendly than a slow, pixel-perfect analysis. The brain relies on built-in visual rules, such as assuming light comes from above, or grouping adjacent shapes using Gestalt continuity. When these priors are exposed to highly artificial, mathematically optimized patterns, the brain's heuristics generate false conclusions. Illusions are simply the natural edge cases where these evolutionary shortcuts break down.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 3 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do optical illusions trick the brain?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Illusions trick the brain by systematically overstimulating or misdirecting specific neural pathways in the visual cortex. For example, physiological motion illusions use alternating high-and-low contrast wedges to manipulate the timing of neural signals reaching the motion-processing area V5 (MT). Because cells process high-contrast borders faster than low-contrast borders, the brain receives delayed signals and interprets the lag as actual motion. Similarly, color illusions exploit lateral inhibition in the retina, where excited photoreceptors suppress neighboring cells, altering the perceived brightness of intersections or adjacent colors.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 4 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>What are optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          Optical illusions are perceptual anomalies where a person's subjective visual experience differs significantly from the objective physical reality of the stimulus. They serve as valuable tools for cognitive scientists and psychologists because they expose the underlying mechanisms of human sight. Rather than representing failures of the eyes, optical illusions demonstrate the complex, active construction of vision. They occur when the sensory receptors in the retina, the relay stations of the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN), and the specialized cortical processing areas V1 through V5 resolve ambiguous or conflicting visual data.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 5 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>What is an optical illusion?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          An optical illusion is a visual mismatch between a physical pattern and its neurological interpretation. It represents a temporary breakdown in the brain's predictive processing model of the world. Under normal circumstances, top-down predictions from the higher visual cortex combine seamlessly with bottom-up inputs from the retina. An optical illusion interrupts this workflow by presenting shapes, contrasts, or perspectives that trigger contradictory templates. This forces the brain to alternate between competing hypotheses or construct physiological errors, demonstrating that what we perceive is not a direct camera feed, but a neural simulation.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 6 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Are optical illusions bad for your eyes?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          No, optical illusions are completely harmless and cannot damage your eyes or brain. They are simply demonstrations of physiological and cognitive thresholds. Some high-contrast repeating grid patterns (like op-art) may cause temporary eye strain, fatigue, or mild headaches due to the rapid micro-saccadic movements required to stabilize the image or the high metabolic activity in visual area V1. If you experience discomfort, looking away for a few moments allows your photoreceptors and extraocular muscles to rest, completely resolving any symptoms without any long-term effects.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 7 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>What are the 3 types of optical illusions?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          The three primary categories are literal, physiological, and cognitive illusions. Literal illusions create visual perceptions that differ from the physical components that form them, such as hidden figures in a landscape. Physiological illusions result from sensory overstimulation of specific pathways in the retina or cortex, leading to neural adaptation and visual fatigue (e.g., Troxler fading or afterimages). Cognitive illusions occur when the brain uses top-down logic and prior assumptions to interpret ambiguous or impossible geometries, such as the Penrose stairs or Kanizsa triangles, causing visual paradoxes.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 8 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>Explain how optical illusions work</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          To explain how optical illusions work, we must analyze the visual pathway. Light enters the eye, hitting photoreceptors in the retina, which convert the signal into electrical impulses. These impulses travel through the optic nerve and lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) to the primary visual cortex (V1). Area V1 maps the contours and orientation of shapes, V4 processes color, and V5 processes motion. Illusions exploit these distinct channels by feeding them confusing inputs. By desensitizing specific color pathways or delaying contrast processing speeds, the brain synthesizes motion, color shifts, or shapes that do not exist physically.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ 9 -->
      <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/40">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full p-5 text-left font-bold text-white flex justify-between items-center hover:bg-slate-900 transition-colors">
          <span>How do optical illusions and how they work?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon text-purple-400 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden p-5 text-sm text-slate-350 border-t border-slate-850 bg-slate-950/20 leading-relaxed">
          This question addresses the dual nature of illusions as both physical drawings and neural phenomena. A physical drawing uses geometric gradients, contrast boundaries, and perspective grids. Neurologically, these layouts trigger predictive coding responses. The brain expects depth, shadow, and movement based on natural environmental statistics. When these drawings violate physical rules—like drawing impossible trident prongs that merge figure and ground—the higher visual cortex experiences cognitive friction. The brain struggles to unify the conflicting inputs, alternating between interpretations, showing that vision is an active inference system.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

